\title: Cycle Decomposition of Permutations

\sec: Statement

Given a permutation $\sigma$, we can write $\sigma$ as a product of pairwise-disjoint cycles

\katex: \sigma = \beta_1 \cdots \beta_n

Such a product is called a \jarg <(cycle|cyclic) decomposition> [cycle decomposition] of $\sigma$.

Cycle decompositions are unique, but only up to ordering, since disjoint cycles permute.


\sec: Example

Consider the permutation

\katex:
  \sigma = \begin{pmatrix}
       1 & 2 & 3 & 4 & 5 & 6 & 7
    \\ 4 & 5 & 3 & 1 & 7 & 6 & 2
  \end{pmatrix}

We can visualize this permutation as so:

\tikz:
  \node[draw,circle] at (0    :2) (1) {1};
  \node[draw,circle] at (51.4 :2) (2) {2};
  \node[draw,circle] at (102.8:2) (3) {3};
  \node[draw,circle] at (154.2:2) (4) {4};
  \node[draw,circle] at (205.7:2) (5) {5};
  \node[draw,circle] at (257.1:2) (6) {6};
  \node[draw,circle] at (308.5:2) (7) {7};

  \begin{scope}[shorten >=5pt, shorten <=5pt, >={latex}]
    \draw[->] (1) to[bend left] (4);
    \draw[->] (4) to[bend left] (1);

    \draw[->] (3) to[loop,out=120,in=60,looseness=6] (3);
    \draw[->] (6) to[loop,out=-120,in=-60,looseness=6] (6);

    \draw[->] (2) to (5);
    \draw[->] (5) to (7);
    \draw[->] (7) to (2);
  \end{scope}

One may notice that this permutation is comprised of a number of cycles. Indeed, we can write it as the product

\katex:
  \begin{align*}
    \sigma &= (4\ 1)(2\ 5\ 7)(3)(6) \\
           &= (4\ 1)(2\ 5\ 7)
  \end{align*}


