\sec: Properties

- Given a cycle decomposition $\sigma = \beta_1 \cdots \beta_n$, the order $\lvert \sigma \rvert$ is equal to the least common multiple $\text{LCM}(\lvert \beta_1 \rvert, \dots, \lvert \beta_n \rvert)$ \aref[rk].
\adef:
  I will not give a proof of this. However, the intuition is that since each product term $\beta_i$ is disjoint with all others, they "act independently" and so the identity will be reached on common multiples.

- If $\sigma$ is a $n$-cycle, then the cycle decomposition of $\sigma^k$ consists of $\ell$-cycles (probably), where $\ell$ is the additive order of $k$ modulo $n$ \aref[more].
\adef:
  Things I don't have:
  - A proof for this
  - A good explanation for this
  - Complete confidence that this is correct

  Things I do have:
  - Pretty pictures for this
  - Relative confidence that this is correcy

  Let us fix $\sigma$ to be the identity 12-cycle. So $n=12$ and $\sigma$ looks like:

  \tikz:
    \foreach \i
      [evaluate=\i as \deg using {int(-30 * \i)}]
      [evaluate=\i as \n using {int(\i + 1)}]
      in {0, ..., 11}
    { \node (\i) at (\deg:2) {\n}; }

    \foreach \i [evaluate=\i as \j using {int(mod(\i + 1, 12))}] in {0, ..., 11}
    { \draw[->] (\i) to (\j); }

  Now consider $\sigma^3$. We can characterize $\sigma$ as taking $x$ to $x + 1$ (bar cyclic behaviour). As such, $\sigma^3$ will take $x$ to $x + 3$ (bar cyclic behaviour). This looks like:

  \tikz:
    \foreach \i
      [evaluate=\i as \deg using {int(-30 * \i)}]
      [evaluate=\i as \n using {int(\i + 1)}]
      in {0, ..., 11}
    { \node (\i) at (\deg:2) {\n}; }

    \foreach \i
      [evaluate=\i as \a using {int(mod(\i + 0, 12))}]
      [evaluate=\i as \b using {int(mod(\i + 3, 12))}]
      [evaluate=\i as \c using {int(mod(\i + 6, 12))}]
      [evaluate=\i as \d using {int(mod(\i + 9, 12))}]
      in {0, ..., 2}
    {
      \draw[->] (\a) to (\b);
      \draw[->] (\b) to (\c);
      \draw[->] (\c) to (\d);
      \draw[->] (\d) to (\a);
    }

  Note that $\sigma$ is composed of 3 distinct 4-cycles. Convince yourself this makes sense, and naturally gives rise to the conjecture that if $k \mid 12$ then $\sigma^{12}$ will be comprised of $(12/k)$-cycles.

  Now consider $\sigma^8$:

  \tikz:
    \foreach \i
      [evaluate=\i as \deg using {int(-30 * \i)}]
      [evaluate=\i as \n using {int(\i + 1)}]
      in {0, ..., 11}
    { \node (\i) at (\deg:2) {\n}; }

    \foreach \i
      [evaluate=\i as \a using {int(mod(\i + 0, 12))}]
      [evaluate=\i as \b using {int(mod(\i + 8, 12))}]
      [evaluate=\i as \c using {int(mod(\i + 16, 12))}]
      [evaluate=\i as \d using {int(mod(\i + 24, 12))}]
      [evaluate=\i as \e using {int(mod(\i + 32, 12))}]
      in {0, ..., 3}
    {
      \draw[->] (\a) to (\b);
      \draw[->] (\b) to (\c);
      \draw[->] (\c) to (\d);
      \draw[->] (\d) to (\e);
      \draw[->] (\e) to (\a);
    }

  Note that $\sigma^8$ is comprised of 4 distinct 3-cycles. Convince yourself this makes sense, and naturally gives rise to the conjecture that the cycle decomposition of $\sigma^k$ consists of cycles of length equal to the additive order of $k$ modulo $12$.

  Generalizing, we have that if $\sigma$ is an $n$-cycle, then $\sigma^k$ comprises $\ell$-cycles, where $\ell = \text{LCM}(n, k)/k$ is the additive order of $k$ modulo $n$.
